<section class="text-center text-white px-5 py-[110px] bg-[linear-gradient(120deg,rgba(2,6,23,.92),rgba(15,23,42,.82)),url(&#39;https://legalx24.com/img/cheque-hero.jpg&#39;)] bg-cover bg-center">
      <h1 class="font-black text-[clamp(34px,4.2vw,48px)]"> Cheque Bounce Cases – Section 138 NI Act </h1>
      <p class="max-w-[900px] mx-auto mt-3 text-[17px] leading-8"> When a cheque issued for payment gets dishonoured, it can create serious financial and legal trouble. Under Section 138 of the Negotiable Instruments Act, cheque bounce is treated as a criminal offence, giving the payee a strong legal remedy to recover the amount and enforce accountability. </p></section><section class="px-5 py-[55px] bg-white">
      <div class="container mx-auto">
         <h2 class="text-[clamp(26px,3vw,34px)] font-extrabold text-slate-950 mb-2 after:block after:w-[65px] after:h-1 after:bg-green-600 after:mt-2"> What is a Cheque Bounce? </h2>
         <p class="text-[16px] text-slate-600 leading-8 mb-2"> A cheque bounce happens when the bank refuses to honour a cheque at the time of presentation. This can occur for several reasons such as insufficient balance, closed account, signature mismatch, stop payment instructions, or exceeding the sanctioned limit. </p>
         <p class="text-[16px] text-slate-600 leading-8 mb-2"> In practical terms, issuing a cheque means giving a written assurance that payment will be made. If that assurance fails, the law allows the affected party to take legal action for recovery. </p>
         <p class="text-[16px] text-slate-600 leading-8"> Cheque bounce provisions exist to maintain trust in financial transactions and protect individuals and businesses from payment defaults. </p>
      </div> </section><section class="px-5 py-[55px] bg-slate-50">
      <div class="container mx-auto">
         <h2 class="text-[clamp(26px,3vw,34px)] font-extrabold text-slate-950 mb-2 after:block after:w-[65px] after:h-1 after:bg-green-600 after:mt-2"> Legal Framework – Section 138 of NI Act </h2>
         <p class="text-[16px] text-slate-600 leading-8 mb-2"> Section 138 of the Negotiable Instruments Act applies when a cheque issued for repayment of a legally enforceable debt is returned unpaid. To proceed legally, the payee must send a demand notice within the prescribed time after receiving the bank return memo. </p>
         <p class="text-[16px] text-slate-600 leading-8 mb-4"> If the drawer does not clear the payment within the statutory period after receiving the notice, a criminal complaint can be filed before the Magistrate. </p>
         <div class="bg-white border-l-[6px] border-green-600 p-6 rounded-[10px] shadow-lg my-6 font-semibold"> Cheque bounce cases can result in imprisonment, fine, or both — which is why they are considered a strong legal tool for recovery. </div>
      </div> </section><section class="px-5 py-[55px] bg-white">
      <div class="container mx-auto">
         <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-2 gap-10 items-center">
            <div>
               <h2 class="text-[clamp(26px,3vw,34px)] font-extrabold text-slate-950 mb-2 after:block after:w-[65px] after:h-1 after:bg-green-600 after:mt-2"> Cheque Bounce Legal Procedure </h2>
               <p class="text-[16px] text-slate-600 leading-8 mb-2"> The process starts once the cheque is dishonoured and the bank issues a return memo mentioning the reason. After that, the payee must send a formal legal notice demanding payment within the statutory time. </p>
               <p class="text-[16px] text-slate-600 leading-8 mb-2"> If payment is still not made, a criminal complaint can be filed in the appropriate Magistrate court. </p>
               <p class="text-[16px] text-slate-600 leading-8"> Maintaining proper documents, following timelines, and filing the case correctly are essential for success in cheque bounce matters. </p>
            </div>
            <div> 
               <img src="https://legalx24.com/img/cheque-1.jpg" class="w-full rounded-[14px] shadow-[0_20px_45px_rgba(0,0,0,.2)]" alt="Cheque Bounce Legal Process" data-themekey="#"/> &#160;</div>
         </div>
      </div> </section><section class="px-5 py-[55px] text-white bg-gradient-to-br from-[#020617] to-slate-900">
      <div class="container mx-auto">
         <h2 class="text-[clamp(26px,3vw,34px)] font-extrabold mb-2 after:block after:w-[65px] after:h-1 after:bg-green-600 after:mt-2"> Why Cheque Bounce Law is Important </h2>
         <p class="text-[16px] leading-8 mb-2"> Cheque bounce law helps maintain discipline in financial dealings and prevents careless or intentional defaults. </p>
         <p class="text-[16px] leading-8 mb-2"> Since the matter involves criminal liability, many disputes get settled quickly once legal action begins. </p>
         <p class="text-[16px] leading-8"> For businesses, lenders, and individuals, this law acts as an effective way to enforce payment and recover dues. </p>
      </div> </section><section class="px-5 py-[55px] bg-white">
      <div class="container mx-auto">
         <h2 class="text-[clamp(26px,3vw,34px)] font-extrabold text-slate-950 mb-2 after:block after:w-[65px] after:h-1 after:bg-green-600 after:mt-2"> Rights of Payee &amp; Drawer </h2>
         <p class="text-[16px] text-slate-600 leading-8 mb-2"> The payee has the right to initiate legal proceedings and seek recovery if a cheque issued in their favour is dishonoured. </p>
         <p class="text-[16px] text-slate-600 leading-8 mb-2"> At the same time, the drawer has the right to receive notice, respond, and defend the case. Courts ensure that the law is used fairly and not for harassment. </p>
         <p class="text-[16px] text-slate-600 leading-8"> The objective is to balance recovery rights with fair legal process. </p>
      </div> </section><section class="px-5 py-[55px] bg-slate-50">
      <div class="container mx-auto">
         <h2 class="text-[clamp(26px,3vw,34px)] font-extrabold text-slate-950 mb-2 after:block after:w-[65px] after:h-1 after:bg-green-600 after:mt-2"> Role of Legal Strategy in Cheque Bounce Cases </h2>
         <p class="text-[16px] text-slate-600 leading-8 mb-2"> Cheque bounce matters are highly timeline-driven. Missing a notice deadline or filing incorrectly can weaken the case. </p>
         <p class="text-[16px] text-slate-600 leading-8"> Proper legal guidance helps ensure correct procedure, strong documentation, and faster resolution. </p>
      </div> </section><section class="text-center text-white px-5 py-[65px] bg-gradient-to-br from-[#052e16] to-[#14532d]">
